      <h1 class="blog-title">Custom Galleries: Photo Collections, Named However You Like</h1>

      <p class="blog-meta">Feature &nbsp;&bull;&nbsp; 5 min read</p>

      <div class="blog-body">

        <p>Legacy Odyssey is a digital baby book — built as a real website at your child's own .com domain. Your baby gets their name as a website. Parents fill in milestones, photos, and letters through the iOS &amp; Android app. Family visits the book at your-childs-name.com, straight from any browser. Password-protected. $29 for the first year.</p>

        <p>The book already has dedicated sections for the big moments — birth, coming home, month by month. Custom Galleries are for everything else worth keeping together: a trip, a season, a theme. You make the gallery, you name it, you fill it.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>What it is</h2>

        <p>A Custom Gallery is a photo collection you create and name yourself. You can make as many as you like, give each one its own title, and add up to 50 photos to each — every photo can have its own caption. Galleries appear on the public book as their own pages, each with a tap-to-enlarge view so visitors can move through the photos one by one.</p>

        <p>You build galleries in My Account at legacyodyssey.com/account/book/galleries, and in the iOS and Android app. Same feature, either way.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>Why it matters</h2>

        <p>Not every set of photos fits a fixed milestone. The first beach day, the nursery coming together, a weekend with cousins, the holidays — these are collections, not single moments. Custom Galleries give you a clean, captioned home for each one, titled in your own words, sitting right inside the book at your child's .com address.</p>

        <p>And because you control the order the galleries appear in, the book reads the way you want it to — newest first, by season, or whatever order tells it best.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>How to use it, step by step</h2>

        <h3>1. Open Custom Galleries</h3>

        <p>Sign in at legacyodyssey.com/account (or open the app) and go to <strong>My Book → Custom Galleries</strong>.</p>

        <h3>2. Create a gallery</h3>

        <p>Tap <strong>+ Create Gallery</strong>. You'll name it on the next page, the same place you add your photos — so there's nothing to fill in twice.</p>

        <h3>3. Name it</h3>

        <p>At the top of the new gallery, type a title in the <strong>Gallery name</strong> field — "Our Trip to the Lake," "The Nursery," "First Christmas" — and tap <strong>Save name</strong>. You can rename it any time.</p>

        <h3>4. Add your photos</h3>

        <p>Tap <strong>Add photos</strong>, then select as many as you like at once. They upload one after another with a progress count, and the gallery holds up to 50. If your connection hiccups mid-batch, uploads retry on their own — you don't lose the whole set over one dropped photo.</p>

        <h3>5. Caption each photo</h3>

        <p>Under any photo, type a label or caption in the box and tap out of it — it saves on its own. Captions are optional, but a few words ("Sophia's first time in the water") go a long way for family looking back later.</p>

        <h3>6. Reorder your galleries</h3>

        <p>Back on the Custom Galleries list, drag the handle (☰) next to any gallery to reorder them. The order you set is the order visitors see on the book. A small note confirms the order saved.</p>

        <h3>7. Edit or remove</h3>

        <p>Open any photo's <strong>Remove</strong> to take it out, use <strong>Rename</strong> on the list to retitle a gallery, or <strong>Delete gallery</strong> to remove a whole collection. Deleting a gallery can't be undone, so it asks first.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>What family sees</h2>

        <p>On the public book at your-childs-name.com, each gallery becomes its own page, reachable from the galleries menu. Visitors see your titled collection laid out cleanly, and tapping any photo opens a larger view they can step through with arrows — left and right through the whole set. Captions show right alongside. It's the same warm, premium look as the rest of the book: cream background, gold accents, nothing cluttered.</p>

        <hr>

        <h2>An example</h2>

        <p>The book is for Sophia Smith at sophiasmith.com.</p>

        <p>Over the summer, Mom takes a run of photos at the lake. She opens Custom Galleries, taps <strong>+ Create Gallery</strong>, names it <strong>Our Trip to the Lake</strong>, and adds twelve photos in one go. She captions a few — "First time in the water," "Asleep before the drive home" — and leaves the rest as they are.</p>

        <p>A month later she makes a second gallery, <strong>The Nursery</strong>, with eight photos of the room coming together. On the list, she drags the lake trip above the nursery so the most recent collection shows first.</p>

        <p>When Grandma opens the book, she sees both galleries in the menu. She taps into the lake trip, taps the first photo, and arrows through all twelve full-size — captions and all — from her couch, in her browser, no app required.</p>

